1️⃣ Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
1. Definition (Interview Answer)
Single Responsibility Principle states that a class should have only one responsibility and only one reason to change.
This principle was popularized by Robert C. Martin.
👉 In simple terms:
A class should focus on one functionality only.
________________________________________
2️⃣ Core Idea Behind SRP
Many developers misunderstand SRP.
It does NOT mean “one method per class.”
It means:
One reason to change
Example reasons to change:
Responsibility	Reason to Change
Database logic	DB schema changes
Email logic	Email provider changes
Business logic	Business rule changes
Logging	Logging strategy changes
If multiple reasons to change exist in one class, it violates SRP.
________________________________________
3️⃣ Real World Example
Consider a restaurant kitchen.
Roles:
•	Chef → cooks food
•	Waiter → serves food
•	Cashier → handles billing
If one person does all tasks, problems occur:
•	slow service
•	hard to manage
•	difficult to scale
Similarly in software:
One class doing everything → bad design.
________________________________________
4️⃣ Bad Example (SRP Violation)
class UserService {

    public void saveUser(User user) {
        // save user to database
    }

    public void sendWelcomeEmail(User user) {
        // send email
    }

    public void generateReport() {
        // generate report
    }
}


Problem
This class handles 3 responsibilities
Responsibility	Why it may change
User persistence	DB schema changes
Email sending	SMTP provider change
Reporting	Business reporting changes
This leads to:
❌ tightly coupled code
❌ difficult testing
❌ difficult maintenance
________________________________________
5️⃣ Correct Design (SRP Applied)
Split responsibilities.
class UserRepository {
    public void saveUser(User user) {
        // DB logic
    }
}
class EmailService {
    public void sendWelcomeEmail(User user) {
        // email logic
    }
}
class ReportService {
    public void generateReport() {
        // report logic
    }
}


Now each class has one responsibility.
________________________________________
6️⃣ How SRP Appears in Real Enterprise Systems
SRP is the reason layered architecture exists.
Typical Spring Boot structure:
Controller
   ↓
Service
   ↓
Repository
Example:
UserController → Handles HTTP request
UserService → Business logic
UserRepository → Database access
Each layer has one responsibility.
This is why frameworks like Spring Boot encourage layered architecture.
________________________________________
7️⃣ Advanced Example (Senior Developer Level)
Bad design:
class OrderService {

    public void createOrder(Order order) {
        validateOrder(order);
        saveOrder(order);
        sendNotification(order);
        generateInvoice(order);
    }
}


Responsibilities:
1️⃣ Validation
2️⃣ Persistence
3️⃣ Notification
4️⃣ Invoice generation
Refactored design:
class OrderValidator { }
class OrderRepository { }
class NotificationService { }
class InvoiceService { }


Service orchestrates them.
class OrderService {

    private OrderValidator validator;
    private OrderRepository repository;
    private NotificationService notificationService;
    private InvoiceService invoiceService;

    public void createOrder(Order order) {

        validator.validate(order);
        repository.save(order);
        notificationService.notify(order);
        invoiceService.generate(order);
    }
}


Now:
✔ high cohesion
✔ low coupling
✔ easy testing
________________________________________
8️⃣ Testing Advantage
Without SRP:
Testing UserService becomes difficult.
With SRP:
You can test each component separately.
Example:
Test UserRepository
Test EmailService
Test ReportService
This greatly improves unit testing with JUnit/Mockito.
________________________________________
9️⃣ Common Interview Trap
Interviewers often ask:
Question
Is it correct to create many small classes to follow SRP?
Best answer:
SRP does not mean creating extremely small classes. It means grouping related responsibilities together so that the class has only one reason to change.
Balance is important.
________________________________________
🔟 Interview Ready Answer (Best Version)
If interviewer asks:
What is Single Responsibility Principle?
You can say:
Single Responsibility Principle states that a class should have only one responsibility and one reason to change. It improves maintainability, readability, and testability of code. In enterprise applications we usually implement it using layered architecture where controllers handle HTTP requests, services contain business logic, and repositories manage database operations.
________________________________________
Senior Developer Tip
SRP improves:
•	Microservice design
•	Clean architecture
•	Testability
•	Code maintainability
