***************************

The **Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)** is the first principle of **SOLID Principles**.

### Definition

**A class should have only one reason to change.**
That means **a class should have only one responsibility (one job).**

❌ **Wrong Design:**
One class handles **business logic + database + printing**.

✅ **Correct Design:**
Separate classes handle **each responsibility**.

---

# 1️⃣ Bad Example (Violates SRP)

Here **one class is doing multiple jobs**:

* Calculate salary
* Save to database
* Print report

```java
class EmployeeService {

    public double calculateSalary(int hours) {
        return hours * 500;
    }

    public void saveEmployee(String name) {
        System.out.println("Saving employee " + name + " to database");
    }

    public void printReport(String name) {
        System.out.println("Printing report for " + name);
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        EmployeeService service = new EmployeeService();

        double salary = service.calculateSalary(10);
        System.out.println("Salary: " + salary);

        service.saveEmployee("Amit");
        service.printReport("Amit");
    }
}
```

### Problem ❌

If requirements change:

| Change                | Class Modified  |
| --------------------- | --------------- |
| Salary logic change   | EmployeeService |
| Database logic change | EmployeeService |
| Printing logic change | EmployeeService |

➡ **One class has multiple reasons to change**
➡ **SRP is violated**

---

# 2️⃣ Good Example (Follows SRP)

Now each class has **only one responsibility**.

### Employee (Data Model)

```java
class Employee {

    private String name;
    private int hours;

    public Employee(String name, int hours) {
        this.name = name;
        this.hours = hours;
    }

    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }

    public int getHours() {
        return hours;
    }
}
```

---

### Salary Calculator (Only salary logic)

```java
class SalaryCalculator {

    public double calculateSalary(Employee emp) {
        return emp.getHours() * 500;
    }
}
```

---

### Employee Repository (Database logic)

```java
class EmployeeRepository {

    public void save(Employee emp) {
        System.out.println("Saving employee " + emp.getName() + " to database");
    }
}
```

---

### Report Printer (Printing responsibility)

```java
class ReportPrinter {

    public void print(Employee emp, double salary) {
        System.out.println("Employee: " + emp.getName());
        System.out.println("Salary: " + salary);
    }
}
```

---

### Main Class (Runnable)

```java
public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Employee emp = new Employee("Amit", 10);

        SalaryCalculator calculator = new SalaryCalculator();
        double salary = calculator.calculateSalary(emp);

        EmployeeRepository repository = new EmployeeRepository();
        repository.save(emp);

        ReportPrinter printer = new ReportPrinter();
        printer.print(emp, salary);
    }
}
```

---

# 3️⃣ Output

```
Saving employee Amit to database
Employee: Amit
Salary: 5000.0
```

---

# 4️⃣ Why This Is SRP ✔

| Class              | Responsibility      |
| ------------------ | ------------------- |
| Employee           | Hold data           |
| SalaryCalculator   | Salary calculation  |
| EmployeeRepository | Database operations |
| ReportPrinter      | Printing            |

Each class has **only one reason to change**.

---

# 5️⃣ Interview Answer (Short Version)

**Question:** What is Single Responsibility Principle?

**Answer:**

> Single Responsibility Principle states that a class should have only one responsibility and only one reason to change.
> For example, instead of one class handling salary calculation, database operations, and report printing, we separate them into different classes like SalaryCalculator, EmployeeRepository, and ReportPrinter.

